  "rule": "Under the Statute of Frauds, a promise to answer for the debt of another (a suretyship/guaranty) is generally unenforceable unless in a signed writing. An exception applies where the promisor’s main purpose in making the promise is to secure a personal economic benefit for himself (the “main purpose” or “leading object” rule), in which case the promise is treated as an original undertaking and may be enforceable without a writing. A separate Statute of Frauds provision requires a writing for contracts that cannot be performed within one year; if performance is possible within one year, no writing is required. A unilateral contract may be formed where the promisor invites acceptance by performance; the offeree’s completion of the requested performance supplies consideration. A mistake about a collateral motive (e.g., a hoped-for tax consequence) generally does not excuse performance absent a basis for rescission (such as mutual mistake about a basic assumption) or a contract term making the obligation conditional on that tax benefit.",
  "application": "The father’s promise is, on its face, a promise to pay the son’s existing debt to a lender, which ordinarily falls within the suretyship provision of the Statute of Frauds and would require a signed writing. However, the facts indicate the father’s primary motivation was to obtain a personal economic benefit (a tax deduction), with additional motives of helping his son and encouraging the marriage. Because the father’s leading object was his own economic advantage, the main-purpose exception likely applies, taking the promise outside the suretyship writing requirement. The one-year provision does not bar enforcement because the condition (marriage within 18 months) could be satisfied within one year (and in fact was satisfied in 14 months), so the agreement was capable of performance within one year. Consideration exists because the father conditioned his promise on the son marrying within a specified time; the son completed that performance, which can constitute acceptance of a unilateral offer even if the son also had independent reasons to marry. The father’s later discovery that he would not qualify for a tax deduction does not, by itself, negate contract formation or provide a defense, since the promise was not expressly conditioned on obtaining the deduction and the mistake concerns the father’s unilateral assumption about tax consequences rather than a mutually shared basic assumption incorporated into the bargain.",
  "conclusion": "Yes. The father’s oral promise is likely enforceable because the main-purpose exception removes it from the Statute of Frauds’ suretyship writing requirement, the contract was capable of performance within one year, the son’s timely marriage supplies consideration, and the father’s mistaken belief about a tax deduction does not excuse performance."
}

